b'' b'from denning:' b'' b'the skipjack encryption algorithm' b'f, an 80-bit family key that is common to all chips' b'n, a 30-bit serial number' b'u, an 80-bit secret key that unlocks all messages encrypted with the chip' b'' b'e[m; k], the encrypted message stream, and' b'e[e[k; u] n; f], a law enforcement block.' b'' b'where the session key is k, and is transmitted encrypted in the unit key u.' b'which along with the serial number n is encrypted in the family key f.' b'' b'presumably the protocol can be recovered (if by nothing else, differential' b'analysis).' b'' b'postulate if you will, a chip (or logic) sitting between the clipper chip' b'and its communications channel. the function of this spoof chip is twofold:' b'' b'1) transmit channel' b'' b'the spoof chip xors the bit encrypted serial number with' b'a secondary keying variable. this renders the serial number' b'unrecoverable with just the family key' b'' b'2) receive channel' b'' b'the spoof chip xors the incoming encrypted serial number' b'with a secondary keying variable (assuming integrity of the' b'law enforcement block is necessary for local operation b'checksums, sequence control, etc.).' b'' b'this has the net result of hiding the serial number. it is probable theere is' b'a known plaintext pattern used as a filler in the block containing n bits' b'as used in generating u, u1,u2) correctness of the law enforcement block' b'can be determined with only the family key f. whereas, no one has proposed' b'federal agencies be denied f, and because they could recover it themselves,' b'the correctness of the serial number can be tested by examining the pad bits' b'of n in e[n; f].' b'' b'the one could selectively alter the law enforcement block as above, but the' b'mutilation could be detected. a better approach would be to mutilate the' b'entire law enforcement block. if it were done with a group encryption scheme' b'such as des or (presumably) skipjack, the chances the law enforcement block' b'can be re